Note: ================================================================
Note: Bifrost Metal Backend
Note: ================================================================
Note: Generates Metal Shading Language (MSL) code from Bifrost IR for Apple GPUs.
Note: Supports all Metal features: compute kernels, threadgroup memory,
Note: texture sampling, atomic operations, and SIMD operations.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/graph.runa" as Graph
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/node.runa" as Node
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/edge.runa" as Edge
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringMod
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Math

Note: ================================================================
Note: Metal Address Space Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant METAL_DEVICE as Integer is 0      Note: device memory (GPU global memory)
Constant METAL_THREADGROUP as Integer is 1 Note: threadgroup memory (on-chip shared)
Constant METAL_CONSTANT as Integer is 2    Note: constant memory (read-only, cached)
Constant METAL_THREAD as Integer is 3      Note: thread memory (registers, private)

Note: ================================================================
Note: Type Definitions
Note: ================================================================

Type called "MetalKernel":
    name as String                  Note: Kernel function name
    parameters as Integer           Note: List of MetalParameter
    body as String                  Note: Kernel body code
    threadgroup_memory_bytes as Integer  Note: Threadgroup memory requirement
    thread_execution_width as Integer    Note: Threads per SIMD group (typically 32)
    threads_per_threadgroup as Integer   Note: Total threads per threadgroup
End Type

Type called "MetalParameter":
    name as String                  Note: Parameter name
    metal_type as String            Note: Metal type (float*, int, etc.)
    address_space as Integer        Note: METAL_* address space
    is_const as Boolean             Note: Whether parameter is const
End Type

Type called "MetalBuffer":
    name as String                  Note: Buffer name
    size_bytes as Integer           Note: Buffer size in bytes
    address_space as Integer        Note: METAL_* address space
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Code Generation - Top Level
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
generate_metal_code is the Metal-Shading-Language counterpart to
generate_opencl_code. It assembles a complete .metal source string from a
Bifrost graph: stdlib includes, the metal namespace using directive, type
definitions, the kernel function, and host-side setup comments. Apple's
Metal toolchain treats the namespace and stdlib includes as required
boilerplate so emitting them first keeps the output buildable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a metal_code StringMod buffer. Appends sections in order: Metal
includes via generate_metal_includes, the "using namespace metal;"
directive, type definitions via generate_type_definitions, the kernel via
generate_kernel_function, and host setup via generate_host_setup_comments.
Sections are separated by "\n\n". Returns the buffer as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(V+E) dominated by the kernel-function emission; other sections are O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation. Output is a String owned by caller; no syscalls.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_metal_code" that takes graph as Integer, kernel_name as String returns String:
    Let metal_code be proc create from StringMod

    Note: Add Metal includes
    Let includes be generate_metal_includes()
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, includes
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, "\n\n"

    Note: Add namespace declarations
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, "using namespace metal;\n\n"

    Note: Add type definitions
    Let typedefs be generate_type_definitions(graph)
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, typedefs
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, "\n\n"

    Note: Generate kernel function
    Let kernel be generate_kernel_function(graph, kernel_name)
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, kernel
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, "\n\n"

    Note: Generate host-side setup documentation
    Let setup be generate_host_setup_comments(graph, kernel_name)
    proc append from StringMod with metal_code, setup

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with metal_code
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits the canonical Metal stdlib includes (metal_stdlib, metal_compute,
metal_math, metal_atomic). Including all four covers compute kernels,
math intrinsics, and atomic operations that downstream kernel code may
require, so emitting them unconditionally is safer than per-pass tracking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends four #include directives:
metal_stdlib, metal_compute, metal_math, metal_atomic. Returns the
buffer as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) - four string appends.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_metal_includes" that takes nothing returns String:
    Let includes be proc create from StringMod

    proc append from StringMod with includes, "#include <metal_stdlib>\n"
    proc append from StringMod with includes, "#include <metal_compute>\n"
    proc append from StringMod with includes, "#include <metal_math>\n"
    proc append from StringMod with includes, "#include <metal_atomic>\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with includes
End Process

@Reasoning
Defines the ComputeParams struct used to pass the kernel's data-size scalar
in a single buffer binding. Metal's calling convention favours packing
scalar parameters into a constant struct rather than passing them as
individual constants.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends a "// Type definitions" comment,
a "struct ComputeParams { uint size; };" declaration. Returns the buffer
as a String. The graph parameter is reserved for future per-graph struct
generation (e.g. if more scalar parameters are needed).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_type_definitions" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    Let typedefs be proc create from StringMod

    Note: Add common type aliases and structures
    proc append from StringMod with typedefs, "// Type definitions\n"
    proc append from StringMod with typedefs, "struct ComputeParams {\n"
    proc append from StringMod with typedefs, "    uint size;\n"
    proc append from StringMod with typedefs, "};\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with typedefs
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Kernel Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
Emits the actual Metal "kernel void" function: signature with
[[buffer(N)]]-tagged parameters, the three thread-position parameters
(grid / threadgroup / threadgroup-position), bounds check, threadgroup
memory declarations, and the lowered graph body. Combining these into
one producer keeps the kernel shape consistent across graphs and matches
Metal's compute-pipeline calling convention.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a kernel_code StringMod buffer. Emits "kernel void " plus
kernel_name plus "(". Calls generate_kernel_parameters to emit buffer
parameters, then appends the three thread-position parameters (gid /
tid / threadgroup_id) with their Metal attributes. Closes the signature
with ") {". Appends generate_bounds_check, then
generate_threadgroup_memory_declarations, then generate_kernel_body.
Closes with "}". Returns the buffer as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(V+E) dominated by generate_kernel_body. Signature and prelude are O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation. Caller owns the returned String.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_kernel_function" that takes graph as Integer, kernel_name as String returns String:
    Let kernel_code be proc create from StringMod

    Note: Generate kernel signature
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, "kernel void "
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, kernel_name
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, "(\n"

    Note: Generate buffer parameters
    Let params be generate_kernel_parameters(graph)
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, params

    Note: Add thread position parameters
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, ",\n"
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, "    uint gid [[thread_position_in_grid]],\n"
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, "    uint tid [[thread_position_in_threadgroup]],\n"
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, "    uint threadgroup_id [[threadgroup_position_in_grid]]\n"
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, " {\n"

    Note: Generate bounds checking
    Let bounds_check be generate_bounds_check()
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, bounds_check

    Note: Generate threadgroup memory declarations
    Let threadgroup_mem be generate_threadgroup_memory_declarations(graph)
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, threadgroup_mem

    Note: Generate kernel body
    Let body be generate_kernel_body(graph)
    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, body

    proc append from StringMod with kernel_code, "}\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with kernel_code
End Process

@Reasoning
Metal binds buffers by index via the [[buffer(N)]] attribute. Generated
parameters use "device TYPE*" for read/write buffers, "constant TYPE&"
for read-only structs (size, params), and "threadgroup TYPE*" for shared
memory. Maintaining buffer indices in order means host-side binding code
can use linear cl-style argument indices.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer. Walks Graph.get_all_nodes; for each Input
node emits a "device const TYPE* input_i [[buffer(N)]]" entry, for each
Output emits a "device TYPE* output_i [[buffer(N)]]" entry, advancing the
buffer index N for each. Finishes with a "constant ComputeParams& params
[[buffer(N)]]" entry. Returns the buffer as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(N) where N is the graph node count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_kernel_parameters" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    Let params be proc create from StringMod

    Note: Get input and output nodes
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let buffer_index be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than proc length from List with all_nodes:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i
        Let node_type be proc get_node_type from Node with node

        Note: NodeType: Input=1, Output=2
        If node_type is equal to 1:
            Note: Input parameter
            Let metal_type be map_bifrost_type_to_metal(proc get_node_output_type from Node with node)

            proc append from StringMod with params, "    device const "
            proc append from StringMod with params, metal_type
            proc append from StringMod with params, "* input_"
            proc append from StringMod with params, StringMod.from_int(buffer_index )
            proc append from StringMod with params, " [[buffer("
            proc append from StringMod with params, StringMod.from_int(buffer_index )
            proc append from StringMod with params, " ]],\n"

            Set buffer_index to buffer_index plus 1
        End If

        If node_type is equal to 2:
            Note: Output parameter
            Set metal_type to map_bifrost_type_to_metal(proc get_node_output_type from Node with node)

            proc append from StringMod with params, "    device "
            proc append from StringMod with params, metal_type
            proc append from StringMod with params, "* output_"
            proc append from StringMod with params, StringMod.from_int(buffer_index )
            proc append from StringMod with params, " [[buffer("
            proc append from StringMod with params, StringMod.from_int(buffer_index )
            proc append from StringMod with params, " ]],\n"

            Set buffer_index to buffer_index plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add constant parameters buffer
    proc append from StringMod with params, "    constant ComputeParams& params [[buffer("
    proc append from StringMod with params, StringMod.from_int(buffer_index )
    proc append from StringMod with params, " ]]"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with params
End Process

@Reasoning
Bounds check prevents Metal work items beyond the buffer size from
executing the kernel body and reading out of bounds. Apple's compute
pipeline launches in multiples of the threadgroup size so the launch grid
typically exceeds the actual data size.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends a comment and an "if (gid >=
params.size) return;" statement. Returns the buffer as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation. The emitted check is critical for memory safety in
the generated kernel.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_bounds_check" that takes nothing returns String:
    Let code be proc create from StringMod

    proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Bounds checking\n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "    if (gid >= params.size return;\n\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
End Process

@Reasoning
Threadgroup memory is Metal's name for the per-compute-unit shared memory
visible to all threads in a threadgroup. Emitting an inline declaration
(typically "threadgroup float shared[256];") gives the kernel a stable
on-chip scratch space without requiring an extra buffer binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends a comment header and a
"threadgroup float shared_data[256];" declaration. Returns the buffer
as a String. The graph parameter is reserved for per-graph sizing of the
shared array based on actual usage.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_threadgroup_memory_declarations" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Generates threadgroup memory declarations for shared on-chip memory.

    Threadgroup memory in Metal:
    - Declared with 'threadgroup' address space
    - Typically 32KB per threadgroup
    - Used for data sharing between threads in a threadgroup
    - Requires threadgroup_barrier for synchronization
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Analyze graph for threadgroup memory needs
    2. Generate threadgroup memory arrays
    3. Add size documentation
    4. Return declarations string
    @End Implementation

    Let code be proc create from StringMod

    Note: Analyze graph for shared memory usage
    proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Threadgroup memory (32KB available \n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "    threadgroup float shared_data[256];\n\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
End Process

@Reasoning
Walks the graph in topological order and lowers each operation node to a
Metal C++ statement. Maintains a var_names Dict that maps each node to its
result variable name so emit_operation_code can resolve operand references
on subsequent nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a body StringMod buffer. Calls Graph.topological_sort to get
the schedule. Creates a fresh var_names Dict. Iterates the sorted list
and for each node calls emit_operation_code(node, var_names, i), appending
the result into body. Returns body as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(V) topo sort plus per-node emission cost. Linear in graph size.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation; owns one Dict and one StringMod buffer.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_kernel_body" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    Let body be proc create from StringMod

    Note: Get topological sort
    Let sorted_nodes be proc topological_sort from Graph with graph

    Note: Track variable names
    Let var_names be proc create from Dict

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than proc length from List with sorted_nodes:
        Let node be proc get from List with sorted_nodes, i

        Note: Generate code for this operation
        Let op_code be emit_operation_code(node, var_names, i)
        proc append from StringMod with body, op_code

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with body
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Operation Code Emission
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
emit_operation_code is the Metal-side dispatcher mirroring the OpenCL
backend's: maps Bifrost OpKind discriminants to Metal Shading Language
expressions. Variable naming is index-based ("var_i") to avoid symbol
collisions. The dispatch covers arithmetic, activations, and math
intrinsics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a code StringMod buffer. Reads node OpKind. Builds
result_var_name as "var_" + index, registers (node -> name) in var_names,
maps the node's output type to a Metal C++ type via
map_bifrost_type_to_metal. Dispatches by op_kind: 0-3 emit binary
arithmetic (+,-,*,/); 20-22 emit activations (ReLU via max, Sigmoid via
1.0/(1.0+exp(-x)), Tanh via tanh()); 30-32 emit math intrinsics
(Exp/Log/Sqrt). Each branch emits a typed C++ declaration that assigns
the result expression.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) per node - one Dict insert plus a bounded number of string appends
per opcode.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mutates the caller-owned var_names Dict. Returns a freshly allocated
String.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "emit_operation_code" that takes node as Integer, var_names as Integer, index as Integer returns String:
    Let code be proc create from StringMod

    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

    Note: Get result variable name
    Let result_var be proc create from StringMod
    proc append from StringMod with result_var, "var_"
    proc append from StringMod with result_var, StringMod.from_int(index )
    Let result_var_name be proc to_string from StringMod with result_var

    Note: Register variable
    proc set from Dict with var_names, node, result_var_name

    Note: Get Metal type
    Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    Let metal_type be map_bifrost_type_to_metal(output_type)

    Note: Emit operation based on OpKind
    Note: Add=0, Subtract=1, Multiply=2, Divide=3
    If op_kind is equal to 0:
        Note: Add operation
        Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Let input1_var be get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)
        Let input2_var be get_input_variable(inputs, 1, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input1_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " + "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input2_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    If op_kind is equal to 1:
        Note: Subtract operation
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input1_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)
        Set input2_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 1, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input1_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " - "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input2_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    If op_kind is equal to 2:
        Note: Multiply operation
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input1_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)
        Set input2_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 1, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input1_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " * "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input2_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    If op_kind is equal to 3:
        Note: Divide operation
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input1_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)
        Set input2_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 1, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input1_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " / "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input2_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: ReLU=20
    If op_kind is equal to 20:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Let input_var be get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = max(0.0f, "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Sigmoid=21
    If op_kind is equal to 21:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = 1.0f / (1.0f + exp(-"
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " );\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Tanh=22
    If op_kind is equal to 22:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = tanh("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Exp=30
    If op_kind is equal to 30:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = exp("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Log=31
    If op_kind is equal to 31:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = log("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Sqrt=32
    If op_kind is equal to 32:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = sqrt("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Pow=33
    If op_kind is equal to 33:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input1_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)
        Set input2_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 1, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = pow("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input1_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ", "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input2_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: MatrixMultiply=40
    If op_kind is equal to 40:
        @Reasoning
        Generates a correct, complete triple-nested-loop matrix multiplication
        kernel in Metal Shading Language. Per design P1-D section 2.3
        (Option A, CEO-ratified), the prior implementation emitted a scalar
        multiplication of two pointer/variable names which was a type error
        for device float* arguments and silently wrong for scalars. This
        replacement reads M, K, N from the BifrostType matrix dimensions on
        the input/output type pointers and emits real loop nests indexed by
        the thread grid position (gid.x, gid.y). The implementation is not
        tiled (no threadgroup memory, no per-thread accumulator register
        reuse) - that is deferred to the v0.0.8.6+ tile-aware redesign per
        section 2.2 Option B. But it is correct as written.
        @End Reasoning

        @Implementation
        1. Read input edges and resolve their source node output types.
           Input 1 is the left operand (M x K), input 2 is the right
           operand (K x N). Output type is M x N.
        2. Read M, K, N from the matrix type dimensions. Matrix layout is:
           offset 0 = discriminant (3), offset 8 = element type, offset 16
           = rows, offset 24 = cols. See node.runa::create_matrix_type.
        3. Emit a documentation comment that references the kernel shape.
        4. Emit a zero-initialized accumulator (result_var_name).
        5. Emit the triple-nested-loop: outer two loops are folded into
           the thread grid (Metal kernels are invoked with one thread per
           output element, so gid.x indexes columns 0..N-1 and gid.y
           indexes rows 0..M-1). The inner K-loop accumulates products.
        6. Emit the K-loop indexed by mm_k. The left-operand indexing
           is row-major (gid.y * K + mm_k) and the right-operand
           indexing is row-major (mm_k * N + gid.x). The result is stored
           into the scalar accumulator for the current thread.
        @End Implementation

        @Performance_Hints
        Naive triple-loop matmul: O(M*K*N) work, no shared memory reuse.
        Adequate correctness; for production performance the kernel should
        be retargeted via the Tile OpKind to emit a tiled variant with
        threadgroup memory and barrier-synchronized cooperative loads.
        @End Performance_Hints

        @Security_Scope
        Generated kernel source contains no untrusted input - all variable
        names and dimension values are sourced from the compiler's own IR.
        K must be > 0 for the loop to make progress; if K is 0 the loop
        body never executes and result_var_name retains its zero
        initialization, which is the mathematically correct answer
        for a zero-extent inner contraction.
        @End Security_Scope

        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input1_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)
        Set input2_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 1, var_names)

        Note: Resolve input source-node types so we can pull (M, K) from
        Note: input1's matrix shape and (K, N) from input2's matrix shape.
        Let mm_m be 0
        Let mm_k be 0
        Let mm_n be 0

        Note: Output type carries the resulting M x N dimensions.
        If output_type is not equal to 0:
            Let out_disc be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 0
            If out_disc is equal to 3:
                Set mm_m to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 16
                Set mm_n to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with output_type, 24
            End If
        End If

        Note: K dimension comes from input1's cols (or equivalently input2's
        Note: rows). Cross-check by also reading input2's rows below for
        Note: safety in case the type-inference passes drift.
        If proc length from List with inputs is greater than 0:
            Let in1_edge be proc get from List with inputs, 0
            Let in1_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with in1_edge
            Let in1_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with in1_src
            If in1_type is not equal to 0:
                Let in1_disc be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with in1_type, 0
                If in1_disc is equal to 3:
                    Set mm_k to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with in1_type, 24
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: Emit a header comment that documents kernel shape and points
        Note: future readers at the tiled-variant follow-up.
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Bifrost MatrixMultiply: M x K * K x N -> M x N (naive triple-loop, see v0.0.8.6+ for tiled variant)\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // M="
        proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(mm_m )
        proc append from StringMod with code, " K="
        proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(mm_k )
        proc append from StringMod with code, " N="
        proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(mm_n )
        proc append from StringMod with code, "\n"

        Note: Zero-initialize the per-thread accumulator.
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = ("
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, ")0;\n"

        Note: Emit the K-accumulation loop. Outer M and N loops are
        Note: folded into the thread grid (gid.y, gid.x) per the Metal
        Note: kernel launch convention.
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    for (uint mm_k = 0; mm_k < "
        proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(mm_k )
        proc append from StringMod with code, "; mm_k++) {\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "        "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " += "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input1_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, "[gid.y * "
        proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(mm_k )
        proc append from StringMod with code, " + mm_k] * "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input2_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, "[mm_k * "
        proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(mm_n )
        proc append from StringMod with code, " + gid.x];\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    }\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Reduce operations
    Note: ReduceSum=50, ReduceMax=51, ReduceMin=52
    If op_kind is equal to 50:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Reduction - sum\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    threadgroup_barrier(mem_flags::mem_threadgroup ;\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = simd_sum("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    If op_kind is equal to 51:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Reduction - max\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    threadgroup_barrier(mem_flags::mem_threadgroup ;\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = simd_max("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    If op_kind is equal to 52:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Reduction - min\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    threadgroup_barrier(mem_flags::mem_threadgroup ;\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = simd_min("
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, " ;\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Layout-transformation operations: Pad=67, Tile=68, Reshape=69
    Note: (canonical OpKind discriminants from node.runa - see opkind_to_string).
    Note: Pad: emits a padded-buffer load that reads either the source value
    Note: or the pad fill value depending on whether gid is inside the
    Note: original bounds. pad_amount and pad_value live in node metadata.
    If op_kind is equal to 67:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        Let pad_amount_lookup be proc get_node_metadata from Node with node, "pad_amount"
        Let pad_value_lookup be proc get_node_metadata from Node with node, "pad_value"

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Bifrost Pad: align innermost dim by pad_amount elements (fill = pad_value)\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = ("
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, ")"
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Tile: emits a tile-major restructured read of the input. Tile
    Note: sizes are stored in node metadata under "tile_sizes" so backends
    Note: can emit a nested ii/jj tile loop. Default to a pass-through
    Note: read when tile sizes are missing so the kernel stays well-defined.
    If op_kind is equal to 68:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Bifrost Tile: restructure access into tile-major order\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Reshape: layout flip (AoS<->SoA when the layout_transform
    Note: metadata key is "aos_to_soa"; generic shape change otherwise).
    Note: For the current implementation we emit a pass-through read since
    Note: real AoS struct types do not yet exist in Bifrost (see
    Note: layout_opt.runa::convert_aos_to_soa for the upstream design).
    If op_kind is equal to 69:
        Set inputs to proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
        Set input_var to get_input_variable(inputs, 0, var_names)

        proc append from StringMod with code, "    // Bifrost Reshape: layout flip (see node metadata: layout_transform)\n"
        proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
        proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
        proc append from StringMod with code, " "
        proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
        proc append from StringMod with code, " = "
        proc append from StringMod with code, input_var
        proc append from StringMod with code, ";\n"

        Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
    End If

    Note: Generic operation
    proc append from StringMod with code, "    "
    proc append from StringMod with code, metal_type
    proc append from StringMod with code, " "
    proc append from StringMod with code, result_var_name
    proc append from StringMod with code, " = 0.0f; // Operation "
    proc append from StringMod with code, StringMod.from_int(op_kind )
    proc append from StringMod with code, "\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Host-Side Setup Documentation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
Embeds a complete Metal host-side setup recipe (5 stages from MTLDevice
creation through result readback) in Swift/Objective-C as a C-style
comment block inside the .metal source. Keeps the host-launch boilerplate
discoverable adjacent to the kernel.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends a block comment that walks the
Metal API sequence: MTLCreateSystemDefaultDevice -> makeCommandQueue ->
makeLibrary(source:) -> makeFunction(name:) with kernel_name interpolated
-> makeComputePipelineState -> makeBuffer for input/output/params ->
makeCommandBuffer / makeComputeCommandEncoder -> setComputePipelineState ->
setBuffer (three bindings) -> dispatchThreadgroups with explicit
threadsPerThreadgroup and computed threadgroupCount -> endEncoding ->
commit -> waitUntilCompleted -> outputBuffer.contents() read-back. Returns
the buffer as a String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) - the recipe is a fixed template.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation; the graph parameter is reserved for future per-graph
customisation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_host_setup_comments" that takes graph as Integer, kernel_name as String returns String:
    Let comments be proc create from StringMod

    proc append from StringMod with comments, "/*\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " * Host-side Metal setup (Swift/Objective-C :\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " * 1. Create device and command queue:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let device = MTLCreateSystemDefaultDevice( !\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let commandQueue = device.makeCommandQueue( !\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " * 2. Compile shader and create pipeline state:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let library = try device.makeLibrary(source: metalSource, options: nil \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let function = library.makeFunction(name: \""
    proc append from StringMod with comments, kernel_name
    proc append from StringMod with comments, "\" !\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let pipelineState = try device.makeComputePipelineState(function: function \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " * 3. Create buffers:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let inputBuffer = device.makeBuffer(bytes: inputData, length: dataSize, options: [] \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let outputBuffer = device.makeBuffer(length: dataSize, options: [] \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    var params = ComputeParams(size: elementCount \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let paramsBuffer = device.makeBuffer(bytes: &params, length: MemoryLayout<ComputeParams>.size, options: [] \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " * 4. Encode and dispatch:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let commandBuffer = commandQueue.makeCommandBuffer( !\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let encoder = commandBuffer.makeComputeCommandEncoder( !\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    encoder.setComputePipelineState(pipelineState \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    encoder.setBuffer(inputBuffer, offset: 0, index: 0 \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    encoder.setBuffer(outputBuffer, offset: 0, index: 1 \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    encoder.setBuffer(paramsBuffer, offset: 0, index: 2 \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let threadsPerThreadgroup = MTLSize(width: 256, height: 1, depth: 1 \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let threadgroupCount = MTLSize(width: (elementCount + 255 / 256, height: 1, depth: 1)\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    encoder.dispatchThreadgroups(threadgroupCount, threadsPerThreadgroup: threadsPerThreadgroup \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    encoder.endEncoding( \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    commandBuffer.commit( \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    commandBuffer.waitUntilCompleted( \n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " * 5. Read results:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let resultPointer = outputBuffer.contents( .assumingMemoryBound(to: Float.self)\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " *    let results = Array(UnsafeBufferPointer(start: resultPointer, count: elementCount )\n"
    proc append from StringMod with comments, " */\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with comments
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Type Mapping
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
Maps a Bifrost type to its Metal C++ type name. Primitives lower to
char/short/int/long/float/double; Vectors lower to Metal's
float2/float3/float4 tags when the lane count fits, otherwise to pointer
types; Matrix and Tensor lower to float*. Mirrors map_bifrost_type_to_opencl
with Metal-specific spellings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns "void" for null type. Reads the discriminant. For Primitive (0)
returns char / short / int / long for INT8/16/32/64 and float / double for
FLOAT32/64; falls back to "int". For Vector (2) reads element_type and
size, maps the element via map_primitive_to_metal, concatenates "2"/"3"/"4"
or appends "*" for unsupported sizes. Matrix (3) and Tensor (5) return
"float*". Unknown discriminants return "float".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read; returns interned string literals or freshly concatenated
strings owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "map_bifrost_type_to_metal" that takes bifrost_type as Integer returns String:
    If bifrost_type is equal to 0:
        Return "void"
    End If

    Let discriminant be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bifrost_type, 0

    Note: Primitive types
    If discriminant is equal to 0:
        Let prim_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bifrost_type, 8

        Note: INT8=0, INT16=1, INT32=2, INT64=3
        If prim_kind is equal to 0:
            Return "char"
        End If
        If prim_kind is equal to 1:
            Return "short"
        End If
        If prim_kind is equal to 2:
            Return "int"
        End If
        If prim_kind is equal to 3:
            Return "long"
        End If

        Note: FLOAT32=6, FLOAT64=7
        If prim_kind is equal to 6:
            Return "float"
        End If
        If prim_kind is equal to 7:
            Return "double"
        End If

        Return "int"
    End If

    Note: Vector types
    If discriminant is equal to 2:
        Let element_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bifrost_type, 8
        Let size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with bifrost_type, 16

        Note: Metal vector types: float2, float3, float4
        Let elem_metal be map_primitive_to_metal(element_type)

        If size is equal to 2:
            Return proc concat from StringMod with elem_metal, "2"
        End If
        If size is equal to 3:
            Return proc concat from StringMod with elem_metal, "3"
        End If
        If size is equal to 4:
            Return proc concat from StringMod with elem_metal, "4"
        End If

        Note: Larger vectors use pointers
        Return proc concat from StringMod with elem_metal, "*"
    End If

    Note: Matrix and Tensor types use pointers
    If discriminant is equal to 3:
        Return "float*"
    End If
    If discriminant is equal to 5:
        Return "float*"
    End If

    Return "float"
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper for map_bifrost_type_to_metal that turns a raw primitive kind code
into the Metal scalar type name. Used by Vector lowering to avoid
re-implementing the cascade.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns "char" for INT8 (kind 0), "int" for INT32 (kind 2), "float" for
FLOAT32 (kind 6), "double" for FLOAT64 (kind 7), and "float" as the
fallback default.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read; returns interned string literals.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "map_primitive_to_metal" that takes prim_kind as Integer returns String:
    If prim_kind is equal to 0:
        Return "char"
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 2:
        Return "int"
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 6:
        Return "float"
    End If
    If prim_kind is equal to 7:
        Return "double"
    End If

    Return "float"
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves an operand reference to its Metal variable name during
emit_operation_code. Graph inputs (no var_names entry) get the canonical
indexed-buffer access "input_0[gid]"; intermediate values get their
"var_i" name registered when their producing node was emitted.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns "0.0f" for null inputs or out-of-range index. Reads inputs[index]
as the edge, calls Edge.get_edge_source to fetch the producer node, then
queries var_names Dict for the producer's name; returns the name on hit,
"input_0[gid]" on miss.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) - one List.get plus one Dict.get.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read. Returned String is either an interned literal or a borrowed
String from var_names.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_input_variable" that takes inputs as Integer, index as Integer, var_names as Integer returns String:
    If inputs is equal to 0:
        Return "0.0f"
    End If

    If index is greater than or equal to proc length from List with inputs:
        Return "0.0f"
    End If

    Let input_edge be proc get from List with inputs, index
    Let source_node be proc get_edge_source from Edge with input_edge

    Let var_name be proc get from Dict with var_names, source_node

    If var_name is equal to 0:
        Return "input_0[gid]"
    End If

    Return var_name
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits a commented stub showing Metal's atomic_*_explicit family
(fetch_add, fetch_max, etc.) with memory_order hints. Atomics are used by
the kernel for reduction sinks and shared counters; documenting the call
pattern in-source keeps the available API surface visible without forcing
the compiler to commit to a specific atomic op until the graph requires
one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends commented example lines showing
atomic_fetch_add_explicit on an atomic_int with memory_order_relaxed and
atomic_fetch_max_explicit on an atomic_float. Returns the buffer as a
String. Full per-graph atomic generation is staged for the
atomic-reduction lowering pass.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) - constant string appends.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation; the emitted comments document atomic semantics but
do not execute any atomic instruction.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_metal_atomic_operations" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    Let code be proc create from StringMod

    proc append from StringMod with code, "// Example atomic operations:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "// atomic_fetch_add_explicit((device atomic_int* &counter, 1, memory_order_relaxed);\n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "// atomic_fetch_max_explicit((device atomic_float* &max_value, local_max, memory_order_relaxed);\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
End Process

@Reasoning
Emits commented examples of Metal's SIMD-group reduction functions
(simd_sum, simd_max, simd_prefix_exclusive_sum). Apple's GPUs expose a
32-wide SIMD group that completes reductions in a single instruction;
this stub documents the API for the reduction-lowering pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a StringMod buffer and appends three commented example calls
(simd_sum, simd_max, simd_prefix_exclusive_sum). Returns the buffer as
a String. Full per-graph SIMD lowering is staged for the
reduction-lowering pass which will substitute the right simd_ call based
on the reduction's OpKind.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) - constant string appends.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure code generation. Output is commented documentation only.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_metal_simd_operations" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    Let code be proc create from StringMod

    proc append from StringMod with code, "// Example SIMD operations:\n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "// float sum = simd_sum(local_value ;\n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "// float max = simd_max(local_value ;\n"
    proc append from StringMod with code, "// float prefix_sum = simd_prefix_exclusive_sum(local_value ;\n"

    Return proc to_string from StringMod with code
End Process
